			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2010</a> paper:</span><br><i>Feature and Meta-Models in Clafer: Mixed, Specialized, and Coupled</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/KacperBąk.html">Kacper Bąk</a>, <a href="../profile/KrzysztofCzarnecki.html">Krzysztof Czarnecki</a>, <a href="../profile/AndrzejWąsowski.html">Andrzej Wąsowski</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-19440-5_7">10.1007/978-3-642-19440-5_7</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t2c.html"><span class="tagM">T2C: Variability</span></a><ul><li> It targets variability and feature modeling, including how features relate to (and can be coupled with) meta-models.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagL">T3C: DSLs</span></a><ul><li> Clafer is presented as a specialized language to express feature/meta-model structures concisely.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagL">T1D: Composition</span></a><ul><li> A major point is the integration/coupling of feature models and meta-models within one notation.
</li></ul></li></ul>
